(Beginner) Quest 1: Introduction to Avalanche Ecosystem
Introduction
Welcome to the first quest of this campaign! It’s time for you to get acquainted with Avalanche and its technology.
In this quest we will be going through the key components and applications of the Avalanche ecosystem as well as Avalanche developer community sites. This quest will provide you with strong foundational knowledge of how Avalanche works, and its key network infrastructure - so you will be able to better appreciate and understand the subsequent quests and exercises. 

For queries on this quest, join our Discord, head to the #avalanche-helpdesk channel and look for this quest's post.
Learning Outcomes
By the end of this quest, you will be able to: 
  • Describe the emergence of the Web3 paradigm
  • Describe the key features of the Avalanche consensus model and the Snowman Protocol
  • Explain what the P-Chain, X-Chain and C-Chain are and describe their differences
  • Know where to engage with the Avalanche developer community

Quest Walkthrough
Step 1: Web1 vs Web2 vs Web3
Before diving into the concepts of the Avalanche ecosystem, let's first talk about the journey of the evolution from Web1 to Web2 to Web3. How does each Web version differ from each other? What are the characteristics of each Web version and how are they used? 
Article: What is Web3? And How does it Differ from Web2 and Web1?

Learning Checklist
  • Web1 is a read-only web with no interaction between users
  • Web2 is a read-write web with user interaction
  • Due to the rise of social media, there is now more emphasis on user-to-user interactions
  • Web3 is a read-write-own web
  • Web3 is trustless, permissionless and decentralized
Step 2: What is Blockchain?
Avalanche is a blockchain ecosystem, but what exactly is a blockchain? Let’s do a brief introduction on blockchains before we get started with exploring Avalanche, just to make sure we’re all aligned!
As mentioned in Step 1, blockchain technology lies in the center of Web3, but what exactly is blockchain and what problems does it solve?

Let's take a look at the video below by Simplilearn to find out about the essentials of what you need to know about blockchain to get started on this campaign.



Learning Checklist
  • A blockchain is a decentralized digital ledger. It is decentralized because there is no single entity in charge of maintaining the ledger
  • A blockchain is like a collection of records linked to each other
  • Every user has a copy of the ledger, data is encrypted by complex algorithms
  • Data on a blockchain is immutable - once created, it cannot be modified
  • Different blockchains use different hashing algorithms to maintain consensus between nodes
Step 3: Avalanche’s Network Infrastructure
Avalanche features three built-in blockchains: Exchange Chain (X-Chain), Platform Chain (P-Chain), and Contract Chain (C-Chain). All three blockchains are validated and secured by all Avalanche validators which is also referred to as the Primary Network.


Avalanche Documentation - Avalanche Platform

The C-Chain is the default smart contract blockchain on Avalanche and enables the creation of any Ethereum-compatible smart contracts. This blockchain is for applications that require total ordering (for faster asset transfers or any other commutative application, use the X-Chain). The C-Chain implements the Snowman consensus protocol (covered in a later step).

The P-Chain is the metadata blockchain on Avalanche and coordinates validators, keeps track of active subnets, and enables the creation of new subnets. The P-Chain also implements the Snowman consensus protocol.

The X-Chain is the default asset blockchain on Avalanche and enables the creation of new assets, exchanging between assets, and cross-subnet transfers. The X-Chain implements the Avalanche consensus protocol (covered in a later step).

Note: Don’t worry too much about the term “subnets” for now, we’ll cover them in much greater detail in the next quest!
Step 4: Differences Between X, P & C-Chains
As seen from the step above, Avalanche’s network infrastructure actually consists of three main blockchains - the X-Chain, P-chain and C-chain. Each of these blockchains serve a different purpose in the Avalanche network. Let’s focus on learning the differences between the three blockchains in this step.
What are the differences between the X, P, and C-chains?

C-Chain
The key difference of the C-Chain is that it uses an Ethereum style address with 0x at the beginning, which can be added to your MetaMask wallet. Most Avalanche Decentralized Finance (DeFi) platforms such as AAVE, Trader Joe, and Benqi work on the C-Chain and are compatible with Metamask.

X-Chain​
The X-Chain is used for sending and receiving funds such as AVAX, however, it is not used for DeFi platforms. The X-Chain cannot be used with MetaMask or similar wallets, but is accessible from the Avalanche web wallet. The address format is different from Ethereum style 0x addresses - it begins with "X-avax" instead. 

P-Chain​
The P-Chain's main function is to allow users to stake AVAX and serve as a validator. If you are a validator or delegating to a validator, then your AVAX rewards will be received on this blockchain. Note that these also differ from Ethereum style 0x addresses - it begins with "P-avax" instead.

Note: You might have noticed that there was the term “validators” mentioned above. If you’re not familiar with the concept of validators in a blockchain context - validators are essentially responsible for verifying transactions on a blockchain. Once transactions are verified, they are added to the distributed ledger. 

Summary
  • X-Chain is used for sending and receiving funds
  • X-Chain can also be used to create and exchanges assets
  • C-Chain is used for smart contracts and DeFi applications
  • P-Chain allows users to stake AVAX and serve as validators
  • P-Chain allows the creation of subnets
Step 5: Consensus Mechanisms
Next, we will move to Avalanche consensus mechanisms, in particular, the Avalanche Consensus Protocol and the Snowman Protocol. But first, let’s understand what a consensus mechanism is and what the purpose it serves.
As mentioned in Step 2, a blockchain is a decentralised, distributed ledger used to record all transactions in a network. Each of these transactions are basically blocks of data. Consensus for blockchain is a procedure in which a blockchain network reaches agreement about the present state of the data in the network. Through this, consensus algorithms establish reliability and trust in the blockchain network.

Different blockchains use different forms of consensus mechanisms. For Avalanche, there are two forms of consensus mechanisms - the Avalanche Consensus Protocol and the Snowman Protocol.

Avalanche Consensus Protocol
What is the Avalanche Consensus Protocol and how does it work? Refer to the site below to find out more. 

Avalanche Consensus

Learning Checklist
  • Consensus is the means by which a series of validators come to an agreement on a decision
  • Consensus protocols facilitate agreement between all of the validators, ensuring that the network has a synchronized view on the data
  • Each validator is a completely independent decision-maker
  • When validators hear a transaction, they vote on whether a transaction is to be Accepted or Rejected
  • A validator makes an initial decision, and then collaborates with the rest of the network to determine whether the network agrees with this decision
  • A validator randomly selects other validators to ask them what they like. It does this over and over again on new randomly selected nodes until it builds up enough data to determine that its probability of being correct is extremely high
 
Snowman Protocol
Snowman Protocol is a chain-optimized consensus protocol that allows for high-throughput, all powered by the Avalanche consensus. Snowman establishes a totally ordered timeline which is typically required for smart contracts.

What is the Snowman consensus protocol?

Learning Checklist
  • Snowman is a chain-optimised consensus protocol–high-throughput, totally-ordered, and great for smart contracts
  • Snowman is powered by the Avalanche consensus protocol. Both the P-Chain and C-Chain implement the Snowman consensus protocol
  • Snowman is the Avalanche consensus protocol, but applied to a linear chain rather than a DAG (Directed Acyclic Graphs)
Step 6: Joining the Avalanche Discord
The Avalanche Discord is where you can meet other developers working on the Avalanche ecosystem, and you can also seek support, guidance, and assistance, especially if you are new to developing on the Avalanche blockchain!
Do follow the instructions below to join the Avalanche Discord channel.

  1. Visit this link to join Avalanche’s Discord server (note that your Discord account must have been created more than 24 hours ago)
  2. Once you reach the Avalanche Discord server, click on the ‘verify-here’ channel and press on ‘Verify’ in the Wick bot message
  3. Verify the captcha, it should be from a bot called Wick in the form of a direct message on Discord
  4. After completing the captcha, head back to the Avalanche Discord channel and click on the #start-here channel
  5. Read through the announcements and click on the Avax emoji to acknowledge in order to be able to access the other public channels.

Troubleshooting: 
  • If the Wick bot flags your account as suspicious, here are some things you can try: 1) Add email and phone verification to your Discord account 2) Create and verify a new Discord account and wait for 24 hours
  • If the link does not work, try using a different web browser (the Safari browser typically faces the most issue with this)
  • If you have issues with the Wick bot, try accessing the link with your phone instead (you’ll need to have Discord installed on your phone). If you manage to get into the Avalanche Discord server via using your phone, then your Discord on your computer should have no problem accessing the server
Step 7: Avalanche Developer Resources
In this step, we’ll go through some essential developer resources you can refer to as you’re building on Avalanche.
Developer Documentation - this provides information on the features of Avalanche Network, creation of subnets and the use of Avalanche APIs.

Avalanche Support - this support guide website has quick start guides, articles, as well as FAQs to answer questions that you may have as you’re developing on Avalanche blockchain. 

Avalanche Smart Contract Tutorials - this is a collection of smart contract tutorials created by the Avalanche development team. 

Avalanche Community Tutorial Contest - Avalanche hosted a contest in 2022 for the community to create development tutorials, this is the collation of the winning entries. A similar contest was held in 2021 as well!

Avalanche Whitepapers - if you’re interested in finding out more in-depth information regarding topics such as Avalanche’s platform, consensus, token or stablecoins, you can read their respective whitepapers here.
Step 8: Avalanche Social Channels
Besides Discord, which you’ve already explored earlier, Avalanche also has other social media platforms like Twitter, Youtube and Reddit where you can interact with the community and other like-minded folks that are interested in Avalanche!
Forum - the Avalanche forum is the gathering place for discussions for anything and everything regarding the Avalanche network.

Medium - this contains news and articles related to the Avalanche platform that can help developers in understanding concepts related to Avalanche network.

Twitter - here you can find the latest news on reports, updates, new features as well as events that can benefit the community.

Reddit - Avalanche also has a Reddit page where the community can ask questions and discuss relevant topics on Avalanche network.

YouTube - the Avalanche Youtube Channel is packed with educational videos for learning, talks on different topics as well as tutorials for developers.
